Does the assumption of homoskedasticity appear tenable?

  1. In the code chunk below, fit a model with schtyp (whether the school is private or public) and write predicting read. Set public schools as the reference group.
d <- d %>% 
  mutate(schtyp = factor(schtyp),
         schtyp = relevel(schtyp, ref = "public"))

m1 <- lm(read ~ write + schtyp, data = d)
summary(m1)

Fill out the below, providing your interpretation of each:

The intercept represents: * The average score for students attending public who scored a zero on the writing measure

The coefficeint for write represents: * For every one unit increase on the writing measure students scored, on average, 0.64 points higher on the reading measure, when controlling for school type (public versus private).

The standard error around the write coefficient indicates: * The uncertainty of the estimate - technically, the standard deviation of the theoretical sampling distribution.

The model accounted for 35% of the variance in reading scores, indicating the joint contribution of school type and writing scores significantly predicted students reading scores (\(p < 0.01\)).

  1. Use Cooks Distance to identify influential cases. What cases are most influential?
d <- d %>% 
  mutate(cooks_d = cooks.distance(m1))

ggplot(d, aes(id, cooks_d)) +
  geom_label(aes(label = id))

Case 175 is the most influential. However, the value is somewhere around 0.06, which is very small and likely not unduly influential.
